text: hi everyone Anthony Fantino here
internets busiest music nerd and it's
time for a review of the new Denzel
Currie album nostalgia 64 Denzel curry
is a young southern rapper from South
Florida who has ties to the Rader clan
which is this southern hip hop outfit
affiliated with MC Space Ghost purp and
him together with the Rader clan are
largely responsible for this resurgence
of dark atmospheric Memphis inspired
hip-hop classic artists like three 6
mafia Juicy J coupes - whose music comes
out in a big way in the music of little
ugly man Space Ghost purp Halik maul and
Denzel - and denzel's take on this very
dark bleak Memphis rap style combines
elements of cloud wraps and very
atmospheric effects at times in his
music as well as modern and hard-hitting
trap rap some chopped and screwed stuff
- and there's a little bit of early
horrorcore eeriness kind of lurching and
some of the songs here - the soldier is
not denzel's first project but he seems
to be gaining more attention than ever
off of this and while at first I didn't
really see the appeal of this thing the
more I listened to it the more that I
saw that there was a lot of potential in
what Denzel is doing at its most surface
level if you're not really digging deep
into this album Denzel essentially
sounds like another young rapper whose
voice is not really that distinct he
just kind of sounds like an aggressive
young dude his instrumentals are very
trap inspired some of the hooks on this
thing are really grimy an in-your-face
and loud kind of like as if they were
Waka Flocka Flame inspired however I
think what's going on on this LP runs a
lot deeper than that for one this is a
pretty dark record and the instrumentals
are incredibly crushing with the bass
like the song dark and violent whose
instrumental is very very spacious and
chilling and even the song Zone 3 one of
the more hard-hitting tracks on this LP
even has a bit of darkness there in the
instrumental coming from the sort of
repetitive sense and Denzel is pretty
consistent throughout this LP until the
very very end with this very morbid and
tortured vibe now though I did like the
beats on this album a lot they really
fit with denzel's aggressive style when
he's trying to
go hard they fit with his ear your style
when he's trying to tell a bit more of a
story just get really dark get kind of
in your head with with something kind of
sickening they really fit the bill but
where I really ended up being the most
impressed with this LP was with denzel's
flow and his lyrics I don't get me wrong
there are moments on this LP kind of
like the song widescreen where Denzel
sort of sounds like just any young
rapper who has a pretty decent flow but
there are moments on this album where it
really feels like he has something sort
of significant to say like on the track
Zone 3 which essentially is a bit of a
grim painting of where he comes from in
South Florida and being someone from
that area there are some Trayvon Martin
references in this track as well as
other moments on this project but what
feels even more cutting is the next song
on here parents where essentially Denzel
is dealing with a few people who he's
describing in some verses who are sort
of the result of crappy parenting we
have a girl who's stripping and getting
naked and letting guys basically take
advantage of her physically just to pay
the bills we have another person who
essentially over spends money all the
time doesn't know what to do with his
life still lives with his mother and on
the song dark and violent we kind of had
this character who sees no other options
in front of him other than committing
crime to kind of get ahead and make a
way for himself in the world and there's
a beat change up a significant beat
change up in the second half of the song
where essentially we're introduced to
the character in the first half of this
track and then we're sort of let into
this first-person view story of him
pulling off a bank heist and another
thing that kind of hit me on this album
is sort of denzel's willingness to sort
of mix these dark aggressive themes with
with things that for him are kind of
either fun or nostalgic I mean obviously
in the title we have a reference to
Nintendo 64 we have rob banks on one
track sort of name checking Charmander
on the song mystical virus we have the
main character of this track screaming
out in pain in fear like he's Sindel the
character from the Mortal Kombat video
game series and even on zone 3 Denzel
paints this picture of a drive-by not
killing somebody who was meant
to kill and then the guys involved in
the drive-by getting out and cutting his
hands off leaving him with nubs like the
Powerpuff Girls you have some more
hard-hitting tracks on here like threats
and and talk that maybe the most
dumb angry just in your face tracks on
this entire LP but still very catchy
really energetic and just kind of
wrapped me up and just how mad they are
really where this album gets kind of
shaky for me is the second cache we have
a bit of a love song on here with like
me where denzel lyrically it's it's not
bad I feel like his flow is a little
less smooth than it is at times and he
sings a little bit toward the end of the
track which doesn't turn out too well in
his favor it's a little confusing to me
considering that he already has a good
singer guesting on this track who
performs really well on the hook but
this isn't even really the worst moment
on the album for me still here I think
Denzel maintains his personality I think
its tracks like bends where in my
opinion because of his flow the lyrical
content on this track which is honestly
a little shallow and his his voice as
well which i think is still kind of yet
to come into its own he sounds like just
any young rapper who's just swagging and
kind of rapping about drugs and material
things and the song denny cascade this
track would be purely generic and
forgettable too if it weren't for the
really epic and dark beat change up in
the second half and the clothes are on
here a bit of cloud wrap with some awful
awful singing and some lyrics that
really just kind of breezed by me it was
just a very uneventful closer still
toward the end of the cell P I admire
denzel's attempts at kind of breaking up
the vibe of this album trying to deliver
something a little different toward the
end but I feel like as the album changes
up its style and just it's emotional
feel denzel drifts away from what his
strong points are I feel like he could
either consistently deliver these dark
tracks which I think he does very well
or find a way to be a little more
captivating or unique on these more
lighthearted and maybe just less serious
songs still not a bad project and and
something that I feel is going to keep
me in to
with whatever this dude is doing next
I'm feeling a light to decent 7:00
transition but if you've given this LP
listen what did you think of it did you
love it hate it why what do you think I
should review next and that's it
